hands_on_practices.solution:
We have the Pauli matrix identity 
$$e^{i t\sigma_y}=\cos t\,I + i\sin t\,\sigma_y$$
since $\sigma_y^2=I$.  Thus
$$|\psi(t)\rangle=U(t)|1\rangle=(\cos t\,I + i\sin t\,\sigma_y)\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix} 
=\cos t\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix}+i\sin t\,\sigma_y\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix}.$$
Noting 
$$\sigma_y\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}-i\\0\end{pmatrix},$$ 
we get
$$|\psi(t)\rangle
=\cos t\begin{pmatrix}0\\1\end{pmatrix}
+i\sin t\begin{pmatrix}-i\\0\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}\sin t\\\cos t\end{pmatrix}.$$
The expectation value is
$$\langle\sigma_x\rangle_t
=\langle\psi(t)|\sigma_x|\psi(t)\rangle
=\begin{pmatrix}\sin t & \cos t\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}\sin t\\\cos t\end{pmatrix}
=2\sin t\cos t
=\sin(2t).$$
